'''Doreen Norton''', [[OBE]], [[Royal College of Nursing|FRCN]] (1 May 1922, [[Dartford, Kent|Dartford]], [[Kent]] – 30 December 2007, [[Worthing]], [[West Sussex]]) was an English nurse, in the 1950s she used research to show that the best treatment and prevention of [[bedsore]]s was removing the pressure by turning the patient.
A fellow of the [[Royal College of Nursing]], Norton was regarded as instrumental in changing nursing practices to effectively treat [[pressure ulcer]]s, a major killer of hospital inpatients.<ref Name="Elliott">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7952519.stm |title=How one nurse helped stop killer bedsores |last=Elliott |first=Jane |date=21 March 2009 |website=BBC News |access-date=21 March 2009}}</ref><ref Name="Dopson">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/doreen-norton-pioneer-in-geriatric-nursing-782520.html |title=Doreen Norton: Pioneer in geriatric nursing |last=Dopson |first=Laurence |date=15 February 2008 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=21 March 2009 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019044038/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/doreen-norton-pioneer-in-geriatric-nursing-782520.html |archive-date=19 October 2010}}</ref>
